description: A data field which describes quality control information
E.g. genomic source
E.g. RANDOM method
Method used to determine the order of bases in a nucleic acid sequence. In FAIR Genomes: SequencingMethod.
Either PAIRED or SINGLE
A machine-readable representation of an instrument (e.g., a sequencer) in a visual format on a surface

Pre-filled, ready-to-use reagent cartridges intented to improve chemistry, cluster density and read length as well as improve quality (Q) scores for this sample. Reagent components are encoded to interact with the sequencing system to validate compatibility with user-defined applications.

Indicates whether a polymerase chain reaction (PCR) was used to prepare this sample. PCR is a method for amplifying a DNA base sequence using multiple rounds of heat denaturation of the DNA and annealing of oligonucleotide primers complementary to flanking regions in the presence of a heat-stable polymerase.

Indicates which target enrichment kit was used to prepare this sample. Target enrichment is a pre-sequencing DNA preparation step where DNA sequences are either directly amplified (amplicon or multiplex PCR-based) or captured (hybrid capture-based) in order to only focus on specific regions of a genome or DNA sample.
Indicates whether any unique molecular identifiers (UMIs) are present. An UMI barcode is a short nucleotide sequence that is used to identify reads originating from an individual mRNA molecule.

In paired-end sequencing, the DNA between the adapter sequences is the insert. The length of this sequence is known as the insert size, not to be confused with the inner distance between reads. So, fragment length equals read adapter length (2x) plus insert size, and insert size equals read lenght (2x) plus inner distance.
The number of nucleotides intended to be ordered from each side of a nucleic acid fragment obtained after the completion of a sequencing process.
A machine-readable representation of information in a visual format on a surface.

The unique number assigned to an instrument (e.g., a sequencer). This could either be the serial number, a unique ID generated by the data provider/owner, or another character string used to identify the instrument
Who was involved in the processing
links to output of files
When the sequencing run took place
When the mapping experiment took place
The source-specific version of the published genome assembly.
The mean number of times a particular locus (site, nucleotide, amplicon, region) was sequenced.
The median number of times a particular locus (site, nucleotide, amplicon, region) was sequenced.
The number of nucleotides successfully ordered from each side of a nucleic acid fragment obtained after the completion of a sequencing process.

In paired-end sequencing, the DNA between the adapter sequences is the insert. The length of this sequence is known as the insert size, not to be confused with the inner distance between reads. So, fragment length equals read adapter length (2x) plus insert size, and insert size equals read lenght (2x) plus inner distance.

Other NGS quality control metrics, including but not limited to (i) sequencer metrics such as yield, error rate, density (K/mm2), cluster PF (%) and phas/prephas (%), (ii) alignment metrics such as QM insert size, GC content, QM duplicated reads (%), QM error rate, uniformity/evenness of coverage and maternal cell contamination, and (iii) variant call metrics such as number of SNVs/CNVs/SVs called, number of missense/nonsense variants, common variants (%), unique variants (%), gender match and trio inheritance check.
A sequence of characters used to uniquely identify a particular run of a test on a particular batch of samples.
A data field which describes the name of the third party company or laboratory that provided services.
The name of the sequencing platform (i.e. brand, name of a company that produces sequencer equipment). In FAIR Genomes: SequencingPlatform.
The name of the product and model number of a manufacturer's genomic (dna) sequencer. In FAIR Genomes: SequencingInstrumentModel.
Percentage of reads with a Phred quality score over 30, which indicates less than a 1/1000 chance that the base was called incorrectly.
Percentage of the target sequence on which 20 or more unique reads were successfully mapped.

Aparatus in the fluidic subsystem where the sheath and sample meet. Can be one of several types; jet-in-air, quartz cuvette, or a hybrid of the two. The sample flows through the center of a fluid column of sheath fluid in the flow cell.
The numerical identifier for the lane or machine unit where a sample was located during nucleotide sequencing.
An Optical Genome Mapping (OGM) experiment
Sample batch lot identifier
A short-read DNA sequencing experiment
This table extends observations with clinical details compatible with phenopacket
The individual that performed the clinical observation (e.g., made the diagnosis, performed the evaluation, etc.)

The assemblage of traits or outward appearance of an individual. It is the product of interactions between genes and between genes and the environment. In medical context,  these are often the symptoms caused by a disease.

Any abnormal condition of the body or mind that causes discomfort, dysfunction, or distress to the person affected or those in contact with the person. The term is often used broadly to include injuries, disabilities, syndromes, symptoms, deviant behaviors, and atypical variations of structure and function.
Clinical measurements collected as part of the clinical observation
Information on whether the patient is a child from two family members who are second cousins or closer
Gene affected by pathogenic variation that is causal for disease of the individual
Causal variant in HGVS notation with optional classification or free text explaining any other molecular mechanisms involved.
An indication that diagnosis is given and the case is no longer considered unsolved.
The date on which a case was considered solved (i.e., when a diagnosis was made)

A drug product that contains one or more active and/or inactive ingredients used by the individual intended to treat, prevent or alleviate the symptoms of disease. Any hormone therapies, gender-related, or otherwise should also be recorded here.
The specific way a therapeutic drug is to be taken, including formulation route of administration, dose, dosing interval, and treatment duration.
A record of a individual's background regarding health, occurrence of disease events and surgical procedures
The date on which contact with the individual was initiated
The date on which contact with the individual was last made
An individual's classification of functioning i.e. disability profile according to International Classification of Functioning and Disability (ICF)
A description of one or more materials used to make a diagnosis
Beacon v2 Individuals PhenotypicFeatures
A reference to a specific clinical observation (e.g., "Ind001_Phen001")
A term denoting a phenotypic feature. E.g. "Abnormality of body height"

An indication if the phenotype was observed or not. The default is "false", in other words the phenotype was observed. Therefore it is only required in cases to indicate that the phenotype was looked for but found to be absent.

Additional terms to characterize and specify the phenotypic abnormalities defined in the Phenotypic abnormality subontology, with respect to severity laterality, age of onset, and other aspects. E.g. Exacerbated by tobacco use
A value that describes the intensity of the phenotype (e.g., "Profound")
History of diagnoses of an individual at a specific timepoints
A reference to a specific clinical observation (e.g., "Ind001_Phen001")
The diagnosis assigned for this particular observation (e.g., "Spinocerebellar ataxia type 34")
A categorical value that groups this individual's age of onset into groups (e.g., "Adult", "18-24 years", etc.)
The age at which manifestations of the disease first appeared (e.g., "P32Y6M1D")
A categorical value that groups this individual's age at diagnosis into groups (e.g., "Adult", "18-24 years", etc.)
The age at which the diagnosis was made (e.g., "P32Y6M1D")
An indication if the diagnosis is present in one or more family members or other relatives
A value that describes the intensity of the disease (e.g., "Profound")
A part of an occurrence of a disease process which is associated with position in the normal progression of the disease (e.g., "acute onset")
The state or status at the point during the visit the diagnosis was given (e.g., "Suspected")
Additional clinical measurements collected as part of the clinical observation
A reference to a specific clinical observation (e.g., "Ind001_Phen001")
A unique code that identifies or categorises this clinical measurement (e.g., "Metabolomics")
A name that describes the clinical measurement (e.g.. "Blood platelet count")
The value that was measured, collected, derived, etc. (e.g. "55345")
A value that specifes the measured value (e.g., "Per Millimeter")
A metabolomics material processing is a protocol application including material enrollments and biomaterial transformations.
A planned process which results in physical changes in a specified input material.
The transfer of a solute from a liquid phase to another immiscible or partially-miscible liquid phase in contact with it.
The filter used in separating of suspended solids from a liquid or gas, usually by forcing a carrier gas or liquid through a porous medium.
The volume of carrier gas passing through a chromatography column in unit time.
A sample preparation technique using a solid adsorbent contained most commonly in a cartridge device, or on a disk to adsorb select species from solution.
Washing is a process by which a material entity acting as contaminant (e.g. excess staining reagent) is removed by application of one or more cycles of solution in flow.
A qualitative or quantitative analysis performed to determine the amount of a particular constituent in a sample or the biological or pharmacological properties of a drug.
Spectrometry where the sample is converted into gaseous ions which are characterised by their mass-to-charge ratio and relative abundance.
A valve that controls the flow of fluids in through the wall of a chamber.
A piece of apparatus that consists of at least an ion source, a mass-to-charge analyser, a detector and a vacuum system and is used to measure mass spectra.
A piece of apparatus that takes an analyte and generates ions which are passed to the rest of a mass spectrometer for analysis.
A piece of apparatus that has the form of a tube with a diameter between 5 to 50 mm and hosts the stationary bed in chromatography.
Any method for the synthesis of polymer membranes that involves the polymer transforming from the liquid phase of the cast solution to the solid phase.
Condition in which variables of the experiment are manipulated to determine the variables effect by comparing to a control condition.
Basic information, annotation or documentation concerning a metabolomics analysis workflow (but not the workflow itself).
Apply analytical methods to existing data of a specific type.
File content or location that encapsulates the analysis workflow, i.e. a sequence of operations to achieve one or more objectives.
The engine used to execute the workflow such as Papermill, Jupyter, Galaxy or Nextflow.
A printed or electronic work offered for distribution.
The analysis has been boxed by a container engine such as Singularity or Docker.
A general term primarily used for digitally stored data such as computer programs and other kinds of information read and written by computers.
Any factor that defines a system and determines (or limits) its performance.
Which data file formats (i.e. defined ways or layouts of representing and structuring data in a computer file, blob, string, message, or elsewhere) are stored and potentially available.
Any socially-agreed upon specifications used such as Common Workflow Language, mzML, ISA-TAB, FAIR Genomes, etc.
A method of analyzing or representing statistical data or a procedure for calculating a statistic, such as principal component analysis, affinity propagation clustering, T-test, etc.
A reference to one or more resources that organises processes in a meaningful way (e.g., data releases, subpopulations, cohorts, etc.)
The source or origin of the record. For example, an organisation, database, system, etc.
The date the record was created at the source
The person who created the record at the source
The date the record was updated at the source
The person who updated the record at the source
A written explanation, observation or criticism added to textual material
